				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">It's covered in the <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/APU_Status" class="postlink">APU status register page</a>. You might keep in mind that $4015 is really two separate registers. There's the control register, which does things when written to. There's the status register, which gives you the current values of things when read. In neither case is there an 8-bit byte that you can write to and read from.
<br />
<br />On that page, it states that reading bit 4 reflects whether the DMC's bytes remaining counter is non-zero. A write of 0 to bit 4 sets the bytes remaining to 0, and a write of 1 to bit 4 when bytes remaining is 0 restarts the DMC sample. If I read that correctly, a write of 1 to bit 4 when the bytes remaining is non-zero has no effect. Don't assume anything beyond what you read, like that there's an internal "last value written to bit 4" which is compared with the current value to see whether it's different, or anything like this.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

